<p>A year after he started his Ph.D. in mathematics at McGill University, Matt Bowen had a problem. &ldquo;I took my qualifying exams and did absolutely horribly on them,&rdquo; he said. Bowen was sure that his scores didn&rsquo;t reflect his mathematical skills, and he resolved to prove it. Last fall he did, when he and his adviser, Marcin Sabok, posted a major advance in the field known as Ramsey theory.</p>
